{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "ORPO [19], requires preference data in the format of prompts paired with rejected and accepted answers.",
    "For the task of NIDS binary classification, we can adapt these methods by treating the true label as the accepted prompt and the inverse of the label as the rejected prompt.",
    "In contrast, KTO [20] does not require paired preference data and instead relies on a series of prompts and corresponding responses along with a series of binary labels indicating wherever the provided response is relevant.",
    "In our case, we use the true label as the accepted response.",
    "Half of the prompts are randomly sampled with relevant responses using the label and the other half are samples as irrelevant by using the inverse of the label."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "ORPO [19], requires preference data in the format of prompts paired with rejected and accepted answers.",
    "In contrast, KTO [20] does not require paired preference data and instead relies on a series of prompts and corresponding responses along with a series of binary labels indicating wherever the provided response is relevant."
